\section{Text output}

The engine's text system, the most-called code in the game (the
overlays invoke [[MSG_PRINT]] alone some 349 times). Text renders on
the hi-res screen through the resident library's font blitter
([[FONT_DRAW]], documented in the \texttt{STUPH} chapter), with the
monitor's window and cursor zero-page variables
([[MON_WNDLFT]]\dots[[MON_CV]]) defining the text region. The
[[$15xx]] addresses below are \texttt{STUPH}'s public jump vectors;
the engine assembles against them as EQUs.

Three printing interfaces, all using the same inline-argument
convention as the file library:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[MSG_PRINT]] --- zero-terminated text follows the [[JSR]];
  [[MSG_AT]] first sets the cursor from X/Y.
\item [[STR_NTH]] --- an inline \emph{pointer} to a string table
  follows the [[JSR]]; X picks the string. Table strings are packed
  with no separators: the last character of each has its high bit
  set. [[STR_FIRST]] prints entry 0; [[STR_NTH_CAP]] capitalizes the
  first letter (for sentence-initial item names --- the flag byte
  [[CAP_FLAG]] doubles as ``seen the first letter'' state).
\item [[PRINT_HEX]] --- A as two hex digits.
\end{itemize}

Characters pass through [[PUTCH]], which treats the four codes from
[[$7C]] up specially: [[$7C]] (\texttt{|}) is a newline, [[$7E]]
(\texttt{\~{}}) newline-then-column-1, [[$7D]] (\texttt{\}})
newline-only-if-needed-then-column-1, and [[$7F]] (in the string
readers) adds the following byte to the column --- a tab. This is why
the game's strings are full of \texttt{|}, \texttt{\}}, and
\texttt{\~{}} characters. The newline path scrolls the text window
via [[TEXT_SCROLL]] when the cursor passes [[MON_WNDBTM]].

